Dec 21 2006 	My fifth time at the Best Western Civic Center	I have stayed here five times, each time for 10 days, starting in 2002. The first year I had one of the small rooms in the back, but then I discovered that there are larger rooms with a queen size bed AND a sofa bed. I don't understand all the reviews about how bad the neighborhood is -- I walk to SOMA night spots alone almost every night and have never had any trouble. And as to being far from public transportation, three bus lines stop at Harrison and Ninth -- the 27 will take you to the Mission where it's an easy transfer to get to Castro Street and the 47 will take you to Market and Van Ness and then on to the Wharf. You can also transfer here to the Muni (underground) or the F Line or any of the Market Street buses. The rooms are very clean and very well equipped -- desk, table and chairs, sofa and coffee table, ironing board, etc. Refrigerator and microwave are a plus and Trader Joe's is just one long block away. There's also a good deli (the Diana Market) a block away on Ninth Street. Desk personnel have always been great and the free parking is terrific -- probably the only place in town that has it. I recommend the BWCC VERY highly and will stay here again this coming fall.	
Nov 12 2006 	Great Value	This motel is located right in downtown San Francisco. I stayed there from Nov. 5 to Nov. 11 2006. It is one of the cheapest in the area but SUPER clean. I disagree with other reviews that claim it's in a bad area. As two women traveling alone we felt completely secure. If you are from a small town, traveling to a big city might be nerve racking in which case ALL areas in San Francisco will seem scary but this is definately NOT a bad area. San Francisco has a lot of homeless people and beggers. Everywhere you go you will see them from the glamourous stores on Market to the truly bad areas in Haight Ashbury.At this Best Western we were within walking distance to Mission Street and Market Street. We had a rental car, but did hop on the bus once to go to Fisherman's Wharf. (Bubba Gump restaurant is great there.) You can easily access the public transportation from hotel or walk to Mission and catch the trolley. The staff was very friendly and all were able to give good directions and recommend various places. They have a washer and dryer available which is very nice. (Who wants to come home with dirty clothes?) We went to all of the big stores on Market Street. The manager of the motel reccomended outlet stores in Vacaville which were GREAT! Our room was the closest to 9th street which is busy like all streets in San Francisco, we left our windows open all night and had no problem sleeping. We are not heavy sleepers but the soundproofing there is good. When we were in the room we usually left the door open (we are from NY so it seemed hot to us, although the locals were wearing winter coats!) The property is fenced in and has free parking. Try finding that somewhere else in San Francisco!This is a lovely property, with great staff and a heated pool! Definately a great value in a very overpriced area. Thank you to Bali and the rest of the staff for making our stay in San Francisco a lot of fun.On Misson street (take a left off of 9th) there is a cosmotolgy school where they have haircuts for $5. It was the best $5 I EVER spent. There is also great shopping on the less touristy areas of the Mission district.	
Nov 4 2006 	Dangerous area at night!	We stayed here for a week in October and the location is awful! The area is renowned for a homeless/drug/crime problems and you can't walk outside at night. That said, the hotel was OK for one of the cheaper ones- very clean and has all the basics you need. If you do go here you must have a car if you want to travel out in the evening or be prepared to pay for taxis. Better still get a hotel around Fishermans Wharf, Cowhill, Russian Hill or Nob Hill areas. Whatever you do don't go past 5th Street after 6pm (nothing to see there anyway)	
Oct 8 2006 	hotel ok worst part of town	For the price, the hotel itself was acceptable. That's where the positives end. This hotel is in the worst part of town. I've traveled all over the world and I have never been so scared about walking to/from my hotel. I was afraid to go out at night! The hotel is near homeless people, drug junkies, addiction clinics, liquor stores, adult video stores, etc. It's a good 6+ blocks any direction to reach public transit...and those are blocks that you want to walk through VERY quickly. The street it's on (9th) is also quite busy all through the night...I had to stuff toilet paper in my ears because the traffic noise level was so high that I couldn't fall asleep otherwise.Unless it's your last resort ( it was mine) and you value your life, find a hotel in a better area.	
Oct 6 2006 	Cheap block of rooms that are clean and spacious in blah neighborhood	This hotel is an oasis in an gritty part of the city, but it is safe for walking in the daytime. I could not get a better rate for a block of 7 rooms for 4 nighs. In the evenings, frankly, you should take the F line streetcar ($1.50 takes you anywhere along the warves...look for the one that reminds you of the Beatles' Yellow Submarine...) or taxi in case you don't enjoy encounters with panhandlers asking for handouts. Across the street at one corner you find &quot;STUD&quot;, a bar where I don't think my wife would visit, and at the other end you have the AIDS healthcare thrift shop.And there is a nice, inexpensive Indian restaurant around the corner, and interesting pub with fien beers up the steet, and the ubiquitous Starbucks at a corner gas station (a big station).Moscone Center is 18-20 mins walk away. 5 mins in taxi after waiting 5-8 mins for taxi. No complaints on housekeeping or management at desk. If you stay, try to be as distant as you can from the street and its noise. And the free parking is secure.	
Sep 7 2006	Hairrison Street Fair	Traveling with a large group is never an easy task, but the staff at the Best Western Civic Center Inn made every effort to make our stay as pleasant as possible. From providing us with a list of nearby restaurants to dine at or being prompt in supplying extra towels or even calling taxis, Valy, the desk clerk, was as accommodating as one could be for a group of 100 rambunctious and wily partiers. We came to San Francisco to attend the Hairrison Street fair over Labor Day weekend and the organization, Bears, put on a great event for us. The Best Western was the host hotel for this fair. Valy was the best and I will be staying here again for next year’s Hairrison Street fair.	
Sep 6 2006	It delivers	Finding a reasonably priced and clean room in San Francisco isn’t always easy to do. Based on prior experiences, many places seem to advertise one way and yet offer a completely different product. Luckily, this time, my dealings with staying in a hotel in SF proved to be more fruitful. Looking for a reasonably priced room, I booked at the Civic Center Best Western Inn. It advertised clean rooms, free breakfast, free parking, free wireless internet, fridge in the room, and pool. It delivered. I now have a solid hotel to depend on when visiting San Francisco.	
Aug 22 2006	Clean rooms free parking and a pool	It has a pool, and it’s heated! The Civic Center Inn Best Western immediately caught my attention, because, let’s face it, not too many hotels in San Francisco have a pool. But this was only one of several positive features that this Inn had to offer. The free parking was a definite plus, as was the continental breakfast in the lobby and the guest laundry. Although this hotel is in the quieter area of the South of Market, that turned out to be a positive. After long days of walking and touring the city by public transportation, which isn’t all that bad if you ask the front desk for some help, it felt good to return to a comfortable bed in a quiet part of the city for some rest. On that note, the rooms were clean, nice, and filled with all the expected amenities of the Best Western brand. The Civic Center Inn was everything I was looking for, probably even more, at a great price. You can’t go wrong by staying here!	
